r; background:{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}};  color:white\" | '''Conservative <br /> 32 seat majority'''\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}};  color:white\" | '''Conservative <br /> 46 seat majority'''\n|}\n\n=== Exit poll ===\nAn [[exit poll]] conducted by [[Ipsos MORI]] for the [[BBC]], [[ITN|ITV]] and [[Sky News]], was published at the end of voting at 10&nbsp;pm, predicting the number of seats for each party.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/election-2019-50765773 |title=Conservatives on course to win majority - exit poll |publisher=BBC News |date=2019-12-13 |access-date=2019-12-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/election-2019-50424263 |title=Check the exit poll forecast for your area |publisher=BBC News |date=2019-12-12 |access-date=2019-12-13}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |Parties\n! style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |Seats\n! style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |Change\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n|[[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |368\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|{{increase}} 51\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n|[[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |191\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|{{decrease}} 71\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}\" |\n|[[Scottish National Party]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |55\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|{{increase}} 20\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n|[[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |13\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|{{increase}} 1\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"{{Plaid Cymru/meta/color}}\" |\n|[[Plaid Cymru]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |3\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|{{decrease}} 1\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"{{Green Party of England and Wales/meta/color}}\" |\n|[[Green Party of England and Wales|Green Party]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |1\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|{{steady}}\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"{{Brexit Party/meta/color}}\" |\n|[[Brexit Party]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |0\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|New party\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"{{Independent (politician)/meta/color}}\" |\n|Others\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |19\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|{{steady}}\n|-\n! colspan=\"4\" |Conservative 86 seat majority\n|}\n\n==Results==\n{{For|further results|Results breakdown of the 2019 United Kingdom general election}}\n{{For|complete results by individual constituency|Results of the 2019 United Kingdom general election}}\n[[File:2019 UK general election constituency map.svg|thumb|right|200px|Equal-area projection of constituencies]]\n\nThe Conservative Party won a [[landslide victory]] securing 365 seats out of 650, giving them an overall majority of 80 in the House of Commons. They gained seats in several Labour Party strongholds in Northern England that were held for decades, which had formed the '[[Red wall (British politics)|red wall]]'. The constituency of [[Bishop Auckland (UK Parliament constituency)|Bishop Auckland]] elected a Conservative for the first time in its 134-year history. In the worst result for the party in more than 80 years,<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2019/12/13/world/europe/uk-general-election-results.html |title=U.K. Election Results Map: How Conservatives Won in a Landslide |last=McCann |first=Allison |date=2019-12-13 |work=The New York Times |access-date=2019-12-13 |last2=Leatherby |first2=Lauren |issn=0362-4331 |last3=Migliozzi |first3=Blacki}}</ref> Labour won 202 seats, a loss of 60 compared to the previous election.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/election-2019-50765773 |title=Johnson returns to power with big majority |date=2019-12-13 |access-date=2019-12-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/election/2019/results |title=Results of the 2019 General Election |publisher=BBC News |access-date=2019-12-13}}</ref> This marked a fourth consecutive general election defeat. The Liberal Democrats won 11 seats, down 1, despite significantly increasing their share of the popular vote. Leader Jo Swinson lost her seat to the SNP, and resigned shortly afterward.\n\nWhile the Conservatives gained support in England and Wales, they lost support in Scotland in the face of a major SNP advance. The Conservatives won in England, advancing by 1.7% and gaining 48 seats to win 345 out of 533, while Labour fell back by 8% and lost 47 seats to win just 180.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election/2019/results/england |title=England results |date=13 December 2019 |accessdate=14 December 2019 |publisher=BBC News}}</ref> Labour won in Wales, though it lost 8% of its 2017 vote share and six seats, retaining 22 out of 40, while the Conservatives advanced by 2.5% and gained six seats, winning 14 in total.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election/2019/results/wales |title=Wales results |date=13 December 2019 |accessdate=14 December 2019 |publisher=BBC News}}</ref> The SNP won by a landslide in Scotland, advancing by 8.1% and gaining 13 seats to win 48 out of 59, gaining several seats from the Conservatives and Labour. The Conservatives lost 3.5% of their 2017 vote share and half their seats, and Labour was reduced to one Scottish MP.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election/2019/results/scotland |title=Scotland results |date=13 December 2019 |accessdate=14 December 2019 |publisher=BBC News}}</ref> Among the Labour MPs who lost their seats in Scotland was [[Lesley Laird]], deputy leader of the [[Scottish Labour Party]] and [[Shadow Secretary of State for Scotland]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-50812695|title=Lesley Laird stands down as Scottish Labour deputy|date=16 December 2019|publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nThe SNP's leader [[Nicola Sturgeon]] described the result as a clear mandate to hold a [[Proposed second Scottish independence referendum|new referendum for Scottish independence]].<ref name=\"Sturgeon 2019 Elec\" />\n\nIn Northern Ireland, nationalist political parties won more seats than unionist ones for the first time. The DUP's leader in Westminster, Nigel Dodds, lost his seat in [[Belfast North (UK Parliament constituency)|Belfast North]].\n\n===Summary===\nA summarised results of the parties that won seats at the election is as follows:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! colspan=2 rowspan=2 | Party\n!           rowspan=2 | Leader\n! colspan=3           | MPs\n! colspan=3           | Votes\n|-\n!\n! Of total\n! class=\"unsortable\" |\n!\n! Of total\n! class=\"unsortable\" |\n|-\n| style=\"background:{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}};\" |\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | <small>[[Boris Johnson]]</small>\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 365\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | {{Percentage|365|650|1|pad=yes}}\n| data-sort-value=\"\" | {{Infobox political party/seats|365|650|hex={{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}}}\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 13,966,565\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 43.6%\n| {{percentage bar|43.6||c={{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}|border-color=#c0c0c0|background-color=#f0f0f0}}\n|-\n| style=\"background:{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}};\" |\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | <small>[[Jeremy Corbyn]]</small>\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 202\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | {{Percentage|202|650|1|pad=yes}}\n| data-sort-value=\"\" | {{Infobox political party/seats|202|650|hex={{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}}}\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 10,269,076\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 32.2%\n| {{percentage bar|32.1||c={{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}|border-color=#c0c0c0|background-color=#f0f0f0}}\n|-\n| style=\"background:{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}};\" |\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Scottish National Party]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | <small>[[Nicola Sturgeon]]</small>\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 48{{refn|name=hanvey|group=n|Includes [[Neale Hanvey]], who was suspended from the party at the time of his election and thus took his seat as an independent.}}\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | {{Percentage|48|650|1|pad=yes}}\n| data-sort-value=\"\" | {{Infobox political party/seats|48|650|hex={{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}}}\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 1,242,380\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 3.9%\n| {{percentage bar|3.9||c={{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}|border-color=#c0c0c0|background-color=#f0f0f0}}\n|-\n| style=\"background:{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}};\" |\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | <small>[[Jo Swinson]]</small>\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 11\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | {{Percentage|11|650|1|pad=yes}}\n| data-sort-value=\"\" | {{Infobox political party/seats|11|650|hex={{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}}}\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 3,696,423\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 11.6%\n| {{percentage bar|7.4||c={{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}|border-color=#c0c0c0|background-color=#f0f0f0}}\n|-\n| style=\"background:{{Democratic Unionist Party/meta/color}};\" |\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Democratic Unionist Party]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | <small>[[Arlene Foster]]</small>\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 8\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | {{Percentage|8|650|1|pad=yes}}\n| data-sort-value=\"\" | {{Infobox political party/seats|8|650|hex={{Democratic Unionist Party/meta/color}}}}\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 244,128\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 0.8%\n| {{percentage bar|0.8||c={{Democratic Unionist Party/meta/color}}|border-color=#c0c0c0|background-color=#f0f0f0}}\n|-\n| style=\"backg