: {{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| [[File:DouglasHogg 20040917.jpg|75px]]\n| [[Douglas Hogg|<small>The Right Honourable</small><br>'''Douglas Hogg'''<br><small>QC</small>]]<br><small>MP for [[Grantham (UK Parliament constituency)|Grantham]]<br>(1945\u2013)</small>\n| <small>5 July</small><br>1995\n| <small>2 May</small><br>1997\n| {{Party shading/Conservative (UK)}} | [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/lords/viscount-hailsham/349 |title=Viscount Hailsham |publisher=UK Parliament |accessdate=24 November 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"background-color: {{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| [[File:No image.svg|75px]]\n| [[Jack Cunningham, Baron Cunningham of Felling|<small>The Right Honourable</small><br>'''Jack Cunningham'''<br><small>DL</small>]]<br><small>MP for [[Copeland (UK Parliament constituency)|Copeland]]<br>(1939\u2013)</small>\n| <small>3 May</small><br>1997\n| <small>27 July</small><br>1998\n| {{Party shading/Labour}} | [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| rowspan=3 {{Party shading/Labour}} | [[Blair ministry|Blair<br><small>(I\u2013III)</small>]]\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.parliament.uk/biographies/lords/lord-cunningham-of-felling/496 |title=Lord Cunningham of Felling |publisher=UK Parliament |accessdate=23 November 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"background-color: {{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| [[File:Official portrait of Mr Nicholas Brown crop 2.jpg|75px]]\n| [[Nick Brown|<small>The Right Honourable</small><br>'''Nick Brown''']]<br><small>MP for [[Newcastle upon Tyne East and Wallsend (UK Parliament constituency)|Newcastle upon<br>Tyne East and Wallsend]]<br>(1950\u2013)</small>\n| <small>27 July</small><br>1998\n| <small>8 June</small><br>2001\n| {{Party shading/Labour}} | [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/nicholas-brown/523 |title=Rt Hon Nicholas Brown MP |publisher=UK Parliament |accessdate=23 November 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"background-color: {{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| [[File:Official portrait of Margaret Beckett crop 2.jpg|75px]]\n| [[Margaret Beckett|<small>The Right Honourable</small><br>'''Margaret Beckett''']]<br><small>MP for [[Derby South (UK Parliament constituency)|Derby South]]<br>(1943\u2013)</small>\n| <small>8 June</small><br>2001\n| <small>27 March</small><br>2002\n| {{Party shading/Labour}} | [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/margaret-beckett/328 |title=Rt Hon Margaret Beckett MP |publisher=UK Parliament |accessdate=23 November 2017}}</ref>\n|}\n\nFrom 2002 the Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food was dissolved and ministerial responsibility formerly transferred to the [[Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs]].\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|group=Note}}\n\n==Citations==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Agricultural organisations based in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Lists of government ministers of the United Kingdom|Agriculture, Fisheries and Food]]\n[[Category:Defunct ministerial offices in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Agriculture ministers of the United Kingdom| ]]\n[[Category:1889 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:2002 disestablishments in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2015}}\nThe '''Minister of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food''' was a United Kingdom cabinet position, responsible for the [[Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food]]. The post was originally named President of the Board of Agriculture and was created in 1889. In 1903, an Act was passed to transfer to the new styled Board of Agriculture and Fisheries certain powers and duties relating to the fishing industry, and the post was renamed President of the Board of Agriculture and Fisheries.\n\nIn 1919, it was renamed Minister of Agriculture and Fisheries. In 1954, the separate position of [[Minister of Food (United Kingdom)|Minister of Food]] was merged into the post and it was renamed Minister of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food. Successive Prime Ministers asked the Minister to upgrade the Ministry to a Department of State taking the title 'Secretary of State', but all refused.{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}\n\nOn 8 June 2001, the Ministry merged with [[Secretary of State for the Environment]] into the office of [[Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs]]. However, the Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food was not formally abolished until The Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food (Dissolution) Order 2002 (S.I. 2002/794) came into force on 27 March 2002.\n\nUntil the Dissolution Order also made the necessary amendments to the law when it did come into force, many statutory functions were still vested in the holder of the office of Minister of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food, rather in the Secretary of State at large. For that reason, in a final twist, [[Margaret Beckett]] had to be appointed formally as the last ever Minister of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food as well as becoming the first Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs.\n\nThe role is currently held by the [[Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs|Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Agriculture, Fisheries and Food]].\n\n== List of Agriculture Ministers and Board Presidents ==\n\n=== Presidents of the Board of Agriculture (1889\u20131903) ===\n\nPost created by the Board of Agriculture Act 1889.<ref>Board of Agriculture Act 1889 (52 and 53 Vict c 30)</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; white-space: nowrap;\"\n|+President of the Board of Agriculture <ref name=\"Cook & Keith\">{{cite book |last1=Cook |first1=Chris |last2=Keith |first2=Brendan |date=1975 |title=British Historical Facts 1830\u20131900 |url=https://archive.org/details