{"title_page": "Le train pour Venise", "text_new": "#REDIRECT [[The Train for Venice]]\n\n{{Rcatshell|\n{{R from alternative language|fr|en}}\n}}\n", "text_old": "#REDIRECT [[The Train for Venice]]\n", "name_user": "2pou", "label": "safe", "comment": "Rcatshell", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Le_train_pour_Venise&redirect=no"}
{"title_page": "Stampa (family)", "text_new": "{{Royal house||surname=Stampa|coat of arms=Coat of arms of the Stampa family.jpg|motto='''Specimen virtutis avit\u00e6'''|country=[[Italy]]|titles=[[Marquess]] of [[Soncino, Lombardy|Soncino]] <br/> [[Marquess]] of [[Parona]] <br/> [[Count]] of the [[Holy Roman Empire]] <br/> [[Count]] of [[Melzo]] <br/> [[Count]] of [[Rivolta d'Adda]] <br/> [[Count]] of [[Montecastello]]  <br/> [[Count]] and [[Lord]] of [[Ferentino]] <br/> [[Lord]] of [[Tromello]]|founder=Carlo Lanfranco Stampa|founding year=[[8th century]]|cadet branches=Casati Stampa di Soncino <br/> Stampa-de Leyva <br/> Stampa di Parona  <br/> Stampa di Ferentino|created by=[[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor]]|coat_of_arms_size=100px}}<br />[[File:IMG 6689 - Milano - Torre di Palazzo Stampa di Soncino - Foto Giovanni Dall'Orto - 8-Mar-2007.jpg|thumb|[[Palazzo Stampa di Soncino, Milan|Palazzo Stampa di Soncino]] in [[Milan]]]]\nThe '''Stampa''' are a well-know family of old [[Nobility of Italy|Italian nobility]] that rose to prominence in the [[15th century|15th century.]] They were [[Grandees of Spain]], members the [[Order of the Golden Fleece|Order]] [[Order of the Golden Fleece|of the Golden Fleece]] and owned many estates throughout the entire [[Italian Peninsula|Italian peninsula]], including a [[Soncino's Castle|Castle]] in [[Soncino, Lombardy|Soncino]], a [[Palazzo Stampa di Soncino, Milan|Palace]] in [[Milan|Milan,]] and countless others in [[Muggi\u00f2]], [[Melzo]], [[Gorgonzola, Milan|Gorgonzola]], [[Rivolta d'Adda]], [[Ferentino]] and [[Rome]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://siusa.archivi.beniculturali.it/cgi-bin/siusa/pagina.pl?TipoPag=prodfamiglia&Chiave=27423|title=SIUSA - Stampa|website=siusa.archivi.beniculturali.it|access-date=2019-10-08}}</ref>. They are related to some of the most important Italian noble [[Nobility|houses]], such as the [[Doria (family)|Doria]], [[House of Sforza|Sforza]], [[House of Gonzaga|Gonzaga]] and [[Visconti of Milan|Visconti]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lombardiabeniculturali.it/archivi/soggetti-produttori/famiglia/MIDD0002B3/|title=Stampa, famiglia (sec. XV - sec. XVIII) \u2013 Archivi storici \u2013 Lombardia Beni Culturali|website=www.lombardiabeniculturali.it|access-date=2019-10-23}}</ref>. \n\n== Early History ==\n[[File:Soncino Castle.jpg|thumb|The Soncino Castle, formerly called ''Castello Sforzesco'', was donated to the Stampa family by [[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor|Charles V]]<ref>{{Cite book|last=Litta|first=Conte Pompeo|title=Famous Italian Families|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>. ]]\nSome historians trace their ancestry back to Carlo Lanfranco [[Lord]] of [[\u00c9tampes]], later governor of [[Milan]] under [[Charlemagne]]. These sources argue that the Stampa settled between [[Milan]] and [[Gravedona]], ruling over the [[Val Bregaglia]] and much of the surrounding regions. The best evidence for this would be the city of [[Stampa]], named so by the family in honour of its ancestors<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_UzEi2tO3LaEC|page=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_UzEi2tO3LaEC/page/n276 271]|quote=stefano stampa atene.|title=Notizie storiche intorno al comune di Gravedona ed alle principali sue famiglie dai tempi pi\u00f9 remoti fino al 1865|last=Stampa|first=Giuseppe|date=1866|publisher=D. Salvi|language=it}}</ref>.  \n\nOthers, such as the Count and historian Pompeo Litta, do not believe these sources, arguing that it was very common for aristocratic families to falsely attribute their origins to [[France]]. One of the earliest documents Litta could find dates back to [[1277]], when the [[Archbishop of Milan|Archbishop]] [[Ottone Visconti]] became [[List of rulers of Milan|Lord of Milan]]; it consists in a list compiled by Ottone himself, granting several privileges to the most influential families of the city, including Arrigo Stampa . \n\nThe Stampa decided of the destiny of Milan on more than one occasion. The first time was in [[1450]], when they helped [[Francesco I Sforza]] become [[Duke of Milan]]. In [[February]] the Venetians had sent an ambassador, Leonardo Venieri, to negotiate the city's surrender and help them defeat Sforza. Giovanni Stampa marched onto Milan with his army and killed Venieri on the stairs of [[Royal Palace of Milan|Palazzo Ducale]], forcing the milanese to surrender to Francesco I. The newly elected [[Duke]] was naturally obliged to the family, and rewarded them with many honours<ref>{{Cite book|last=Litta|first=Conte Pompeo|title=Famous Italian Families|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>. \n\n== Stampa di Soncino ==\nIn [[1536]] Massimiliano Stampa was created [[Marquess]] of [[Soncino, Lombardy|Soncino]] by [[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor]]. The family ruled over [[Milan]] until [[1876]], and the city flourished immensely under their guidance. Massimiliano Cesare Stampa, the last Marquess of Soncino, died without children and donated his [[Soncino's Castle|castle]] to the [[Soncino, Lombardy|city]]. His title and assets were then taken over by the Casati family, thus creating a new branch called Casati Stampa di Soncino'''.''' \n\n==== Marques of Soncino Stampa (1536-1876) ====\n\n* '''Massimiliano I''' ([[1536]]-[[1543]]), Count, then 1st Marquess of Soncino from 1536\n* '''Ermes I''' ([[1543]]-[[1557]]), Marquess of Soncino, brother of Massimiliano I\n* '''Massimiliano II''' ([[1557]]-[[1596]]), 3rd  Marquess of Soncino, son of Ermes I. Married to Marianna de Leyva, aunt of [[The Nun of Monza|Suor Virginia de Leyva]]\n* '''Ermes II''' ([[1596]]-[[1621]]), 4th Marquess of Soncino, son of Massimiliano II\n* '''Massimiliano III''' ([[1621]]-[[1659]]), 5th Marquess of Soncino, son of Ermes II, sentenced to death for murder\n* '''Giovanni I''' ([[1659]]-[[1678]]), 6th Marquess of Soncino, brother of Massimiliano III\n* '''Massimiliano IV''' ([[1678]]-[[1693]]), 7th Marquess of Soncino, son of Giovanni I\n* '''Giuseppe I''' ([[1693]]-[[1735]]), 8th Marquess of Soncino, brother of Massimiliano IV\n* '''Massimiliano V Giovanni''' ([[1735]]-[[1769]]), 9th Marquess of Soncino, son of Giuseppe I\n* '''Massimiliano VI Giuseppe''' (1769-1818), 10th Marquess of Soncino, son of Massimiliano V Giovanni, [[Grandee|Grandee of Spain]] e Member of the [[Order of the Iron Crown]], married to Carlotta [[House of Gonzaga|Gonzaga]] in 1785\n* '''Massimiliano VII Giovanni''' ([[1818]]-[[1824]]), 11th Marquess of Soncino, son of Massimiliano VI Giuseppe\n* '''Massimiliano VIII''' ([[1824]]-[[1834]]), 12th Marquess of Soncino, son of Massimiliano VII Giovanni\n* '''Massimiliano IX Giovanni''' ([[1834]]-[[1876]]), 13th Marquess of Soncino, son of Massimiliano VIII and last Marquess of Soncino\n\n: ''After Massimiliano IX Giovanni's death, the Casati inherited the title of Marquess of Soncino, which was held unofficially by Camillo Casati Stampa from 1876 to 1892''\n\n==== Casati Stampa, Marquess of Casate (1876-1970) ====\n\n* '''Camillo I''', Marquess of Casate ([[1892]]-[[1946]]), husband of [[Luisa Casati]].\n* '''Camillo II''', Marquess of Casate ([[1946]]-[[1970]]), son of Camillo I. His infamous suicide marked the end of the dynasty.<ref>Franco Avenia, ''IL MARCHESE, LA MOGLIE, L'AMANTE, ECCO LA CHIAVE SCIENTIFICA DI UN MEMORABILE DELITTO'', da: \"l'attimo fuggente\", 2008 {{Cite web|url=http://www.attimo-fuggente.com/archivio20082009/22008/62008/14=scienza3Avenia=62008.htm|title=Copia archiviata|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101130132925/http://www.attimo-fuggente.com/archivio20082009/22008/62008/14=scienza3Avenia=62008.htm|archivedate=30 November 2010|accessdate=4 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Stampa di Ferentino ==\n[[File:Palazzo Stampa di Ferentino.jpg|alt=Palazzo Stampa|thumb|Palazzo dei Conti Stampa di Ferentino in [[Rome]]]]\nIn the early years of the [[18th century]] the Count Pietro Antonio Stampa of Milan settled in [[central Italy]] and married a [[noblewoman]] from [[Frosinone]]. In [[1779]] Pietro's youngest son Angelo was created [[First|1st]] [[Count]] and [[Lord]] of [[Ferentino]]<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=Libro d'Oro della Nobilt\u00e0 Italiana|publisher=|year=1921|isbn=|location=|pages=440}}</ref> with the consent of [[Pope Pius VI]]. He and his brother Filippo had been serving the [[History of the papacy|papacy]] since [[Pope Clement XIV]] appointed them state administrators of the [[Duchy of Castro]] in [[1770]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.comune.ferentino.fr.it/index.php?id_sezione=669|title=Famous citizens of Ferentino (Filippo Stampa)|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>. \n\nAmong their many properties the Stampa had [[Elba]], an island in the [[Mediterranean Sea|Mediterranean]], which they administered since [[Pope Gregory VII|Gregory VII]] granted them the concession on the mine caves. When [[Napoleon]] conquered [[Elba]] and seized the mines, [[Pope Pius VII]] offered the count Domenico Stampa an important job within the [[Papal State|Papal States]] to compensate him for the financial damage he suffered. The [[Cardinal (Catholic Church)|Cardinal]] [[Pope Pius IX|Mastai Ferretti]] (later [[Pope Pius IX]]) also ensured that Domenico contracted a good marriage with Paolina Vinciguerra, the last heir of the count Antonini di [[Alatri]]<ref>{{Cite book|title=Appunti personali del Conte Filippo Maria Stampa|last=Stampa|first=Filippo M.|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>. \n\nThe family continues to exist in [[Rome]] and [[Milan]].\n\n== Notable members ==\n\n* Massimiliano Stampa I, [[Politician]]\n* Stefano Stampa, [[Writer]] and [[stepson]] of [[Alessandro Manzoni]]\n*[[Gaspara Stampa]], [[16th century]] [[poetess]].\n*[[Carlo Gaetano Stampa]], [[Archbishop of Milan]]\n* Massimiliano IX Giovanni, [[Patriot]]\n*[[Ermete Stampa]], [[Bishop of Novara]]\n* Giorgio Stampa, [[Discalced Carmelite]]\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stampa (family)}}\n\n[[Category:Noble families]]\n[[Category:Italian nobility]]\n", "text_old": "{{Royal house||surname=Stampa|coat of arms=Coat of arms of the Stampa family.jpg|motto='''Specimen virtutis avit\u00e6'''|country=[[Italy]]|titles=[[Marquess]] of [[Soncino, Lombardy|Soncino]] <br/> [[Marquess]] of [[Parona]] <br/> [[Count]] of the [[Holy Roman Empire]] <br/> [[Count]] of [[Melzo]] <br/> [[Count]] of [[Rivolta d'Adda]] <br/> [[Count]] of [[Montecastello]]  <br/> [[Count]] and [[Lord]] of [[Ferentino]] <br/> [[Lord]] of [[Tromello]]|founder=Carlo Lanfranco Stampa|founding year=[[8th century]]|cadet branches=Casati Stampa di Soncino <br/> Stampa-de Leyva <br/> Stampa di Parona  <br/> Stampa di Ferentino|created by=[[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor]]|coat_of_arms_size=100px}}<br />[[File:IMG 6689 - Milano - Torre di Palazzo Stampa di Soncino - Foto Giovanni Dall'Orto - 8-Mar-2007.jpg|thumb|[[Palazzo Stampa di Soncino, Milan|Palazzo Stampa di Soncino]] in [[Milan]]]]\nThe '''Stampa''' rose to prominence in the [[Middle Ages|middle ages]]. They were [[Grandees of Spain]], members the [[Order of the Golden Fleece|Order]] [[Order of the Golden Fleece|of the Golden Fleece]] and owned many estates throughout the entire [[Italian Peninsula|Italian peninsula]], including a [[Soncino's Castle|Castle]] in [[Soncino, Lombardy|Soncino]], a [[Palazzo Stampa di Soncino, Milan|Palace]] in [[Milan|Milan,]] and countless others in [[Muggi\u00f2]], [[Melzo]], [[Gorgonzola, Milan|Gorgonzola]], [[Rivolta d'Adda]], [[Ferentino]] and [[Rome]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://siusa.archivi.beniculturali.it/cgi-bin/siusa/pagina.pl?TipoPag=prodfamiglia&Chiave=27423|title=SIUSA - Stampa|website=siusa.archivi.beniculturali.it|access-date=2019-10-08}}</ref>. They are related to some of the most important Italian noble [[Nobility|houses]], such as the [[Doria (family)|Doria]], [[House of Sforza|Sforza]], [[House of Gonzaga|Gonzaga]] and [[Visconti of Milan|Visconti]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lombardiabeniculturali.it/archivi/soggetti-produttori/famiglia/MIDD0002B3/|title=Stampa, famiglia (sec. XV - sec. XVIII) \u2013 Archivi storici \u2013 Lombardia Beni Culturali|website=www.lombardiabeniculturali.it|access-date=2019-10-23}}</ref>. \n\n== Early History ==\n[[File:Soncino Castle.jpg|thumb|The Soncino Castle, formerly called ''Castello Sforzesco'', was donated to the Stampa family by [[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor|Charles V]]<ref>{{Cite book|last=Litta|first=Conte Pompeo|title=Famous Italian Families|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>. ]]\nSome historians regard Carlo Lanfranco [[Lord]] of [[\u00c9tampes]], later governor of [[Milan]] under [[Charlemagne]], as the [[patriarch]] of the [[Aristocratic family|family]]. These sources argue that the Stampa settled between [[Gravedona]] and [[Milan]], ruling over the [[Val Bregaglia]] and much of the surrounding regions. The best evidence for this would be the city of [[Stampa]], named so by the family in honour of its ancestors<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_UzEi2tO3LaEC|page=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_UzEi2tO3LaEC/page/n276 271]|quote=stefano stampa atene.|title=Notizie storiche intorno al comune di Gravedona ed alle principali sue famiglie dai tempi pi\u00f9 remoti fino al 1865|last=Stampa|first=Giuseppe|date=1866|publisher=D. Salvi|language=it}}</ref>.  \n\nOthers, such as the count and historian Pompeo Litta, do not believe these sources, arguing that it was very common for aristocratic families to falsely attribute their origins to [[France]]. The earliest document Litta could find dates back to [[1277]], when the [[Archbishop of Milan|Archbishop]] [[Ottone Visconti]] became [[List of rulers of Milan|Lord of Milan]]; it consists in a list compiled by Ottone himself, granting several privileges to the most influential families of the city, including Arrigo Stampa . \n\nThe Stampa decided of the destiny of Milan on more than one occasion. The first time was in [[1450]], when they helped [[Francesco I Sforza]] become [[Duke of Milan]]. In [[February]] the Venetians had sent an ambassador, Leonardo Venieri, to negotiate the city's surrender and help them defeat Sforza. Giovanni Stampa marched onto the city with his army and killed Venieri on the stairs of [[Royal Palace of Milan|Palazzo Ducale]], forcing Milan to surrender to Francesco I. The newly elected [[Duke]] was naturally obliged to the family, and rewarded them with many honours<ref>{{Cite book|last=Litta|first=Conte Pompeo|title=Famous Italian Families|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>. \n\n== Stampa di Soncino ==\nIn [[1536]] Massimiliano Stampa was created [[Marquess]] of [[Soncino, Lombardy|Soncino]] by [[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor]]. The family ruled over [[Milan]] until [[1876]], and the city flourished immensely under their guidance. Massimiliano Cesare Stampa, the last Marquess of Soncino, died without children and donated his [[Soncino's Castle|castle]] to the [[Soncino, Lombardy|city]]. His title and assets were then taken over by the Casati family, thus creating a new branch called Casati Stampa di Soncino'''.''' \n\n==== Marques of Soncino Stampa (1536-1876) ====\n\n* '''Massimiliano I''' ([[1536]]-[[1543]]), Count, then 1st Marquess of Soncino from 1536\n* '''Ermes I''' ([[1543]]-[[1557]]), Marquess of Soncino, brother of Massimiliano I\n* '''Massimiliano II''' ([[1557]]-[[1596]]), 3rd  Marquess of Soncino, son of Ermes I. Married to Marianna de Leyva, aunt of [[The Nun of Monza|Suor Virginia de Leyva]]\n* '''Ermes II''' ([[1596]]-[[1621]]), 4th Marquess of Soncino, son of Massimiliano II\n* '''Massimiliano III''' ([[1621]]-[[1659]]), 5th Marquess of Soncino, son of Ermes II, sentenced to death for murder\n* '''Giovanni I''' ([[1659]]-[[1678]]), 6th Marquess of Soncino, brother of Massimiliano III\n* '''Massimiliano IV''' ([[1678]]-[[1693]]), 7th Marquess of Soncino, son of Giovanni I\n* '''Giuseppe I''' ([[1693]]-[[1735]]), 8th Marquess of Soncino, brother of Massimiliano IV\n* '''Massimiliano V Giovanni''' ([[1735]]-[[1769]]), 9th Marquess of Soncino, son of Giuseppe I\n* '''Massimiliano VI Giuseppe''' (1769-1818), 10th Marquess of Soncino, son of Massimiliano V Giovanni, [[Grandee|Grandee of Spain]] e Member of the [[Order of the Iron Crown]], married to Carlotta [[House of Gonzaga|Gonzaga]] in 1785\n* '''Massimiliano VII Giovanni''' ([[1818]]-[[1824]]), 11th Marquess of Soncino, son of Massimiliano VI Giuseppe\n* '''Massimiliano VIII''' ([[1824]]-[[1834]]), 12th Marquess of Soncino, son of Massimiliano VII Giovanni\n* '''Massimiliano IX Giovanni''' ([[1834]]-[[1876]]), 13th Marquess of Soncino, son of Massimiliano VIII and last Marquess of Soncino\n\n: ''After Massimiliano IX Giovanni's death, the Casati inherited the title of Marquess of Soncino, which was held unofficially by Camillo Casati Stampa from 1876 to 1892''\n\n==== Casati Stampa, Marquess of Casate (1876-1970) ====\n\n* '''Camillo I''', Marquess of Casate ([[1892]]-[[1946]]), husband of [[Luisa Casati]].\n* '''Camillo II''', Marquess of Casate ([[1946]]-[[1970]]), son of Camillo I. His infamous suicide marked the end of the dynasty.<ref>Franco Avenia, ''IL MARCHESE, LA MOGLIE, L'AMANTE, ECCO LA CHIAVE SCIENTIFICA DI UN MEMORABILE DELITTO'', da: \"l'attimo fuggente\", 2008 {{Cite web|url=http://www.attimo-fuggente.com/archivio20082009/22008/62008/14=scienza3Avenia=62008.htm|title=Copia archiviata|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101130132925/http://www.attimo-fuggente.com/archivio20082009/22008/62008/14=scienza3Avenia=62008.htm|archivedate=30 November 2010|accessdate=4 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Stampa di Ferentino ==\n[[File:Palazzo Stampa di Ferentino.jpg|alt=Palazzo Stampa|thumb|Palazzo dei Conti Stampa di Ferentino in [[Rome]]]]\nIn the early years of the [[18th century]] the count Pietro Antonio Stampa di Milan settled in [[central Italy]] and married a [[noblewoman]] from [[Frosinone]]. In [[1779]] Pietro's youngest son Angelo was created [[First|1st]] [[Count]] and [[Lord]] of [[Ferentino]]<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=Libro d'Oro della Nobilt\u00e0 Italiana|publisher=|year=1921|isbn=|location=|pages=440}}</ref> with the consent of [[Pope Pius VI]]. He and his older brother Filippo had been serving the [[History of the papacy|papacy]] since [[Pope Clement XIV]] appointed them state administrators of the [[Duchy of Castro]] in [[1770]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.comune.ferentino.fr.it/index.php?id_sezione=669|title=Famous citizens of Ferentino (Filippo Stampa)|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>. \n\nAmong their many properties the Stampa had [[Elba]], an island in the [[Mediterranean Sea|Mediterranean]], which they administered since [[Pope Gregory VII|Gregory VII]] granted them the concession on the mine caves. When [[Napoleon]] conquered [[Elba]] and seized the mines, [[Pope Pius VII]] offered the count Domenico Stampa an important job within the [[Papal State|Papal States]] to compensate him for the financial damage he suffered. The [[Cardinal (Catholic Church)|Cardinal]] [[Pope Pius IX|Mastai Ferretti]] (later [[Pope Pius IX]]) also ensured that Domenico contracted a good marriage with Paolina Vinciguerra, the last heir of the count Antonini di [[Alatri]]<ref>{{Cite book|title=Appunti personali del Conte Filippo Maria Stampa|last=Stampa|first=Filippo M.|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>. \n\nThe family continues to exist in [[Rome]] and [[Milan]].\n\n== Notable members ==\n\n* Massimiliano Stampa I, [[Politician]]\n* Stefano Stampa, [[Writer]] and [[stepson]] of [[Alessandro Manzoni]]\n*[[Gaspara Stampa]], [[16th century]] [[poetess]].\n*[[Carlo Gaetano Stampa]], [[Archbishop of Milan]]\n* Massimiliano IX Giovanni, [[Patriot]]\n*[[Ermete Stampa]], [[Bishop of Novara]]\n* Giorgio Stampa, [[Discalced Carmelite]]\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stampa (family)}}\n\n[[Category:Noble families]]\n[[Category:Italian nobility]]\n", "name_user": "MarcoDel7", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stampa_(family)"}
{"title_page": "Macon County, Illinois", "text_new": "{{Short description|County in Illinois}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox U.S. county\n| county           = Macon County\n| state            = Illinois\n| ex image         = Wabash Railroad Station and Railway Express Agency.JPG\n| ex image cap     = [[Wabash Railroad Station and Railway Express Agency]] in Decatur\n| seal             =\n| founded          = 19 January 1829\n| seat wl          = Decatur\n| largest city     = Decatur\n| area_total_sq_mi = 586\n| area_land_sq_mi  = 581\n| area_water_sq_mi = 5.2\n| area percentage  = 0.9\n| population_as_of = 2010\n| population_total = 110768\n| pop_est_as_of    = 2018\n| population_est   = 104712\n| population_density_sq_mi = auto\n| time zone        = Central\n| web              = www.co.macon.il.us/\n| district         = 13th\n| named for        = [[Nathaniel Macon]]\n}}\n'''Macon County''' is a [[County (United States)|county]] located in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Illinois]]. According to the [[2010 United States Census]], it had a population of 110,768.<ref name=QF>{{cite web|title=State & County QuickFacts |url=http://quickfacts.census.gov/qfd/states/17/17115.html |publisher=US Census Bureau|accessdate=July 7, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606203451/http://quickfacts.census.gov/qfd/states/17/17115.html|archivedate=June 6, 2011}}</ref> Its [[county seat]] is [[Decatur, Illinois|Decatur]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.naco.org/Counties/Pages/FindACounty.aspx|accessdate=7 June 2011|title=Find a County|publisher=National Association of Counties|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110531210815/http://www.naco.org/Counties/Pages/FindACounty.aspx|archivedate=31 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nMacon County comprises the Decatur, IL [[Metropolitan Statistical Area]].\n\n==History==\nMacon County was formed on January 19, 1829 out of [[Shelby County, Illinois|Shelby County]]. It was named for [[Nathaniel Macon]], a Colonel in the [[American Revolutionary War|Revolutionary War]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Gannett|first=Henry|author-link=Henry Gannett|title=The Origin of Certain Place Names in the United States|url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_9V1IAAAAMAAJ|year=1905|publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office|page=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_9V1IAAAAMAAJ/page/n194 195]}}</ref> Macon later served as [[United States Senate|senator]] from [[North Carolina]] until his resignation in 1828. In 1830, future US President [[Abraham Lincoln]] and his family moved to Macon County.\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Macon County Illinois 1829.png|Macon County (1829)\nFile:Macon County Illinois 1839.png|Macon County (1829\u20131841)\nFile:Macon County Illinois 1841.png|Macon County (1841\u20131843)\nFile:Macon County Illinois 1843.png|Macon County (1843\u2013present)\n</gallery>\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:Plaque honoring the soldiers of Macon County Illinois who fought in the Civil War.jpg|right|thumb|Plaque honoring Macon County soldiers in the Civil War, 1861-65]]\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau|US Census Bureau]], the county has a total area of {{convert|586|sqmi}}, of which {{convert|581|sqmi}} is land and {{convert|5.2|sqmi}} (0.9%) is water.<ref name=CD/>\n\nMacon County is primarily flat, as is most of the state and all of the surrounding counties, the result of geological activity during the [[Pleistocene]] epoch. During the [[Illinoian (stage)|Illinoian Stage]] of the Pleistocene, the [[Laurentide Ice Sheet]] covered about 85 percent of Illinois, including the Macon County area. The subsequent thaw of the region and retreat of the ice sheet left central Illinois with its present characteristic flat [[topography]].<ref>Stiff, B. J., and A.K. Hansel, 2004, ''Quaternary glaciations in Illinois.'' in Ehlers, J., and P.L. Gibbard, eds., pp. 71-82, ''Quaternary Glaciations: Extent and Chronology 2: Part II North America'', Elsevier, Amsterdam. {{ISBN|0-444-51462-7}}</ref>\n\nBecause of its central location, Macon County is often referred to as \"The Heart of Illinois.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.co.macon.il.us/visitors.php|title=Visitors Information - Macon County Illinois|website=www.co.macon.il.us|accessdate=1 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170907234735/http://www.co.macon.il.us/visitors.php|archivedate=7 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Climate and weather===\n{{climate chart\n|[[Decatur, Illinois]]\n|17|35|2.05\n|22|41|1.95\n|32|53|3.20\n|42|65|3.58\n|52|76|4.47\n|61|85|3.90\n|65|88|4.54\n|63|86|4.14\n|55|80|2.98\n|44|68|2.74\n|34|52|3.32\n|23|39|2.87\n|float=right\n|units=imperial\n|clear=both\n|source=The Weather Channel<ref name=WX>{{cite web|url=http://www.weather.com/weather/wxclimatology/monthly/graph/USIL0302|title=Monthly Averages for Decatur IL|accessdate=27 January 2011|publisher=The Weather Channel|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121023160952/http://www.weather.com/weather/wxclimatology/monthly/graph/USIL0302|archivedate=23 October 2012}}</ref>}}\nIn recent years, average temperatures in the county seat of Decatur have ranged from a low of {{convert|17|\u00b0F}} in January to a high of {{convert|88|\u00b0F}} in July, although a record low of {{convert|-25|\u00b0F}} was recorded in February 1905 and a record high of {{convert|113|\u00b0F}} was recorded in July 1954.  Average monthly precipitation ranged from {{convert|1.95|in}} in February to {{convert|4.54|in}} in July.<ref name=WX/>\n\n===Major highways===\n{{div col|colwidth=15em}}\n* [[Image:I-72.svg|20px]] [[Interstate 72]]\n* [[Image:US 36.svg|20px]] [[U.S. Route 36 in Illinois|U.S. Route 36]]\n* [[Image:US 51.svg|20px]] [[U.S. Route 51 in Illinois|U.S. Route 51]]\n* [[Image:Illinois 48.svg|20px]] [[Illinois Route 48]]\n* [[Image:Illinois 105.svg|20px]] [[Illinois Route 105]]\n* [[Image:Illinois 121.svg|20px]] [[Illinois Route 121]]\n* [[Image:Illinois 128.svg|20px]] [[Illinois Route 128]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Adjacent counties===\n{{div col}}\n* [[De Witt County, Illinois|De Witt]] - north\n* [[Piatt County, Illinois|Piatt]] - northeast\n* [[Moultrie County, Illinois|Moultrie]] - southeast\n* [[Shelby County, Illinois|Shelby]] - south\n* [[Christian County, Illinois|Christian]] - southwest\n* [[Sangamon County, Illinois|Sangamon]] - west\n* [[Logan County, Illinois|Logan]] - northwest\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1830= 1122\n|1840= 3039\n|1850= 3988\n|1860= 13738\n|1870= 26481\n|1880= 30665\n|1890= 38083\n|1900= 44003\n|1910= 54186\n|1920= 65175\n|1930= 81731\n|1940= 84693\n|1950= 98853\n|1960= 118257\n|1970= 125010\n|1980= 131375\n|1990= 117206\n|2000= 114706\n|2010= 110768\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=104712\n|estref=<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2016.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=June 9, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170529192346/https://census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2016.html|archivedate=May 29, 2017}}</ref>\n|align-fn=center\n|footnote=US Decennial Census<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census.html|title=US Decennial Census|publisher=US Census Bureau|accessdate=July 7, 2014}}</ref><br>1790-1960<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mapserver.lib.virginia.edu|title=Historical Census Browser|publisher=University of Virginia Library|accessdate=July 7, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120811110448/http://mapserver.lib.virginia.edu/|archivedate=August 11, 2012}}</ref> 1900-1990<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/population/cencounts/il190090.txt|title=Population of Counties by Decennial Census: 1900 to 1990|publisher=US Census Bureau|accessdate=July 7, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140424084443/http://www.census.gov/population/cencounts/il190090.txt|archivedate=April 24, 2014}}</ref><br>1990-2000<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/population/www/cen2000/briefs/phc-t4/tables/tab02.pdf|title=Census 2000 PHC-T-4. Ranking Tables for Counties: 1990 and 2000|publisher=US Census Bureau|accessdate=July 7, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218203824/http://www.census.gov/population/www/cen2000/briefs/phc-t4/tables/tab02.pdf|archivedate=December 18, 2014}}</ref> 2010-2013<ref name=QF/>\n}}\n\nAs of the [[2010 United States Census]], there were 110,768&nbsp;people, 45,855&nbsp;households, and 29,326&nbsp;families residing in the county.<ref name=DP1>{{cite web|url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_DP/DPDP1/0500000US17115|title=Profile of General Population and Housing Characteristics: 2010 Demographic Profile Data|accessdate=12 July 2015|publisher=US Census Bureau|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213033518/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_DP/DPDP1/0500000US17115|archive-date=February 13, 2020|url-status=dead}}</ref> The population density was {{convert|190.8|PD/sqmi}}. There were 50,475 housing units at an average density of {{convert|86.9|/sqmi}}.<ref name=CD>{{cite web|url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/GCTPH1.CY10/0500000US17115|accessdate=12 July 2015|title=Population, Housing Units, Area, and Density: 2010 - County|publisher=US Census Bureau|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200212201808/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/GCTPH1.CY10/0500000US17115|archive-date=February 12, 2020|url-status=dead}}</ref> The racial makeup of the county was 79.3% white, 16.3% black or African American, 1.0% Asian, 0.2% American Indian, 0.7% from other races, and 2.5% from two or more races. Those of Hispanic or Latino origin made up 1.9% of the population.<ref name=DP1/> In terms of ancestry, 21.7% were [[Germans|German]], 17.0% were [[Americans|American]], 12.9% were [[Irish people|Irish]], and 10.8% were [[English people|English]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/10_5YR/DP02/0500000US17115|title=Selected Social Characteristics in the United States \u2013 2006-2010 American Community Survey 5-Year Estimates|accessdate=12 July 2015|publisher=US Census Bureau|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213012636/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/10_5YR/DP02/0500000US17115|archive-date=February 13, 2020|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOf the 45,855&nbsp;households, 29.5% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 45.7% were married couples living together, 14.1% had a female householder with no husband present, 36.0% were non-families, and 30.9% of all households were made up of individuals. The average household size was 2.33 and the average family size was 2.89. The median age was 40.3 years.<ref name=DP1/>\n\nThe median income for a household in the county was $44,337 and the median income for a family was $57,570. Males had a median income of $48,570 versus $31,568 for females. The per capita income for the county was $24,726. About 10.3% of families and 15.7% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 26.1% of those under age 18 and 6.5% of those age 65 or over.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/10_5YR/DP03/0500000US17115|title=Selected Economic Characteristics \u2013 2006-2010 American Community Survey 5-Year Estimates|accessdate=12 July 2015|publisher=US Census Bureau|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213010547/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/10_5YR/DP03/0500000US17115|archive-date=February 13, 2020|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Communities==\n===Cities===\n* [[Decatur, Illinois|Decatur]]\n* [[Macon, Illinois|Macon]]\n* [[Maroa, Illinois|Maroa]]\n\n===Villages===\n{{div col|colwidth=15em}}\n* [[Argenta, Illinois|Argenta]]\n* [[Blue Mound, Illinois|Blue Mound]]\n* [[Forsyth, Illinois|Forsyth]]\n* [[Harristown, Illinois|Harristown]]\n* [[Long Creek, Illinois|Long Creek]]\n* [[Mount Zion, Illinois|Mount Zion]]\n* [[Niantic, Illinois|Niantic]]\n* [[Oreana, Illinois|Oreana]]\n* [[Warrensburg, Illinois|Warrensburg]]\n{{div col end}}\n[[Image:Map of Macon County Illinois.png|thumb|250px|Map of Macon County]]\n\n===Census-designated place===\n* [[Boody, Illinois|Boody]]\n\n===Unincorporated communities===\n{{div col|colwidth=15em}}\n* [[Bearsdale, Illinois|Bearsdale]]\n* [[Bulldog Crossing, Illinois|Bulldog Crossing]]\n* [[Elwin, Illinois|Elwin]]\n* Heman<ref>[https://www.google.com/maps/place/Heman,+IL+62573/@39.9469994,-89.1144167,15z/data=!3m1!4b1!4m13!1m7!3m6!1s0x8874b9209563b00d:0x39388b2b1e011514!2sMacon+County,+IL!3b1!8m2!3d39.8949055!4d-89.0179332!3m4!1s0x8874ca8fd8070589:0x16c20cc3bac6ec8a!8m2!3d39.9469898!4d-89.1056442 ''Heman, Macon County IL''  Google Maps (accessed 28 December 2018)]</ref>\n* Hervey City<ref>[https://www.google.com/maps/place/Hervey+City,+IL+62549/@39.7556072,-88.8596825,15z/data=!3m1!4b1!4m5!3m4!1s0x8874a69142d33b9d:0x858607ca1238cb58!8m2!3d39.7555916!4d-88.8509063 ''Hervey City, Macon County IL''  Google Maps (accessed 28 December 2018)]</ref>\n* [[Oakley, Illinois|Oakley]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Townships===\n{{div col|colwidth=15em}}\n* [[Austin Township, Macon County, Illinois|Austin]]\n* [[Blue Mound Township, Macon County, Illinois|Blue Mound]]\n* [[Decatur Township, Macon County, Illinois|Decatur]]\n* [[Friends Creek Township, Macon County, Illinois|Friends Creek]]\n* [[Harristown Township, Macon County, Illinois|Harristown]]\n* [[Hickory Point Township, Macon County, Illinois|Hickory Point]]\n* [[Illini Township, Macon County, Illinois|Illini]]\n* [[Long Creek Township, Macon County, Illinois|Long Creek]]\n* [[Maroa Township, Macon County, Illinois|Maroa]]\n* [[Milam Township, Macon County, Illinois|Milam]] (former, now defunct, after merger with Mount Zion Township)\n* [[Mount Zion Township, Macon County, Illinois|Mount Zion]]\n* [[Niantic Township, Macon County, Illinois|Niantic]]\n* [[Oakley Township, Macon County, Illinois|Oakley]]\n* [[Pleasant View Township, Macon County, Illinois|Pleasant View]]\n* [[South Macon Township, Macon County, Illinois|South Macon]]\n* [[South Wheatland Township, Macon County, Illinois|South Wheatland]]\n* [[Whitmore Township, Macon County, Illinois|Whitmore]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Politics==\nIn its early years Macon County favored the Democratic Party, voting for it in every election through 1856. Republican Abraham Lincoln won the county in his landmark 1860 election, and from then until the Great Depression Macon County became solidly Republican, only giving a narrow plurality to [[Woodrow Wilson]] in 1912 when the GOP was mortally divided by Theodore Roosevelt's splinter\u2013party run.\n\nThe FDR-era [[New Deal]] saw the county turn Democratic again due to its strong industrial base, although Macon was a perfect [[bellwether]] between 1932 and 1996 apart from the Catholicism-influenced 1960 election and the 1988 election heavily influenced by [[1988\u201389 North American drought|a major Midwestern drought]]. [[Al Gore]] did narrowly hold the county in 2000 despite losing the election due to [[United States presidential election in Florida, 2000|a razor-thin loss in Florida]], but since then the county has trended Republican. Illinois-bred [[Barack Obama]] did win Macon County in his 2008 triumph, but was convincingly defeated by [[Mitt Romney]] in 2012, whilst in 2016 Hillary Clinton suffered the worst Democratic loss since [[George McGovern]].\n{{Hidden begin\n|titlestyle = background:#ccccff;\n|title      = Presidential elections results\n}}\n{| align=\"center\" border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"float:right; margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 100%;\"\n|+ '''Presidential elections results'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uselectionatlas.org/RESULTS|title=Atlas of US Presidential Elections|first=David|last=Leip|website=uselectionatlas.org|accessdate=1 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=