FIGURES -->308,000+<!-- ROUNDED DOWN TO NEAREST 1,000 --><ref name=\"JHU CSSE\" /><ref name=WOM/>\n| deaths          = <!-- USE BROAD FIGURES -->83,000+<!-- ROUNDED DOWN TO NEAREST 1,000 --><ref name=\"JHU CSSE\" /><ref name=WOM/>\n| territories     = <!-- USE BROAD FIGURES -->220+<!-- ROUNDED DOWN TO NEAREST 10 --><ref name=\"JHU CSSE\" /><ref name=WOM/>\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = \n}}\n<!--\n\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] is an ongoing [[pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19), caused by<nowiki> </nowiki><!--NO DEFINITE ARTICLE (\"THE\") AS PER VIRUS'S ARTICLE-->[[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2]] (SARS-CoV-2).<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus disease 2019 |url=https://www.who.int/emergencies/diseases/novel-coronavirus-2019 |publisher=[[World Health Organization]] |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref> The outbreak was first identified in [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], China, in December 2019, and was recognized as a [[pandemic]] by the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) on 11 March 2020.<ref name=\"WHOpandemic2\">{{cite web |url=https://www.who.int/dg/speeches/detail/who-director-general-s-opening-remarks-at-the-media-briefing-on-covid-19---11-march-2020 |title=WHO Director-General's opening remarks at the media briefing on COVID-19 \u2013 11 March 2020 |date=11 March 2020 |publisher=[[World Health Organization]]|access-date=11 March 2020}}</ref> As of 4 April, more than 1,100,000 cases of COVID-19 have been reported in over 220<!--USE BROAD FIGURES, ROUNDED DOWN TO NEAREST 10--> [[List of countries of the world|countries]] and [[Disputed states|territories]], resulting in more than 83,000 deaths <!--ROUNDED DOWN TO NEAREST MULTIPLE OF 1000--> and 308,000 recoveries.<ref name=\"JHU CSSE\" /><ref name=\"WOM\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/|title=Coronavirus Update (Live): 284,712 Cases and 11,842 Deaths from COVID-19 Virus Outbreak - Worldometer|website=www.worldometers.info}}</ref>\n\n==Comparing the SARS outbreaks==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+Compared Spread of SARS outbreaks (as of 9 April 2020 for SARS-CoV-2)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bnonews.com/index.php/2020/02/the-latest-coronavirus-cases/|title=Tracking coronavirus: Map, data and timeline|last=News|first=B. N. O.|date=18 February 2020|website=BNO News|access-date=4 March 2020}}</ref>\n!Name\n!Countries \n!Confirmed \n!Deaths\n|-\n|[[2002\u20132004 SARS outbreak]]\n|29 \n|8,000+\n|774\n<br />\n|-\n|[[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n|220+ (includes unrecognized or partially recognized territories) \n|2,000,000+\n|101,579+\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n* [[SARS outbreak]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{portal bar|Medicine|Viruses|Coronavirus disease 2019|Pandemic}}\n\n[[Cate degory:COVID-19]]\n[[Category:Severe acute respiratory syndrome]]\n[[Category:21st-century epidemics]]\n[[Category:Infectious disease-related lists|SARS]]\n", "text_old": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=List of SARS outbreaks|timestamp=20200409084407|year=2020|month=April|day=9|substed=yes}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=List of SARS outbreaks|date=9 April 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\nThere have been two SARS outbreaks that have affected either some parts of population or most of the world. In 2002, [[SARS-CoV]] virus strain is responsible for the [[SARS outbreak|2002-2004 epidemic of SARS virus]] which had infected over 8000 and had killed nearly 800.\n\nThe [[SARS-CoV-2]] is responsible for the [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic]]. [[SARS-CoV-2]] has a much lower [[case fatality rate|case fatality ratio (CFR)]] than [[SARS-CoV]], however, it is much more viable for spread. The 2019-20 pandemic has been described as the worst since the [[Spanish flu]]<ref>https://www.starbeacon.com/news/coronavirus/1918-pandemic-similar-in-many-ways-to-todays-covid-19/article_b2e1c0bc-20ab-5820-8836-52671bda59c4.html</ref> and as the most impactful global event since [[World War II]].<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-52114829 | title=Coronavirus outbreak 'greatest test since WW2'| work=BBC News| date=April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==2002\u20132004 SARS outbreak==\n{{main|2002\u20132004 SARS outbreak}}\n\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2002\u20132004 SARS outbreak\n| width           = \n| map1            = SARS map.svg\n| legend1         = A map of the infected countries of the epidemic of SARS between 1 November 2002 and 7 August 2003{{legend|#2B2B2B|Countries with confirmed deaths}}{{legend|#FF2929|Countries with confirmed infections}}{{legend|#B9B9B9|Countries without confirmed cases}}\n| map2            = Sars Cases and Deaths.pdf\n| legend2         = A map of SARS cases and deaths around the world regarding the global population\n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| map4            = \n| legend4         = \n| map5            = \n| legend5         = \n| disease         = [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS]]\n| virus_strain    = [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus|SARS-CoV]]\n| location        = [[World]]wide\n| first_case      = 16 November 2002\n| arrival_date    = \n| origin          = [[Shunde District|Shunde]], [[Guangdong]], [[China]]\n| confirmed_cases = 8,096\n| suspected_cases = \n| recovery_cases  = \n| deaths          = 774\n| territories     = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = \n}}\n[[File:2003 Probable cases of SARS - Worldwide.svg|400px|thumb|2003 Probable cases of SARS - Worldwide]]\n\nThe 2002\u20132004 SARS outbreak was an epidemic involving the [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|severe acute respiratory syndrome (SARS)]] virus, which originated in [[Foshan]], China during November of 2002. Over 8,000 people were infected, and at least 774 died worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/deadly-sars-virus-history-2003-in-photos-2020-2|title=How SARS terrified the world in 2003, infecting more than 8,000 people and killing 774|publisher=businessinsider.com|date=20 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic==\n{{main|2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic\n| map1            = COVID-19 Outbreak World Map per Capita.svg{{!}}upright=1.5\n| legend1         = {{Center|Map of confirmed cases per capita as of 21 March 2020}}\n{{Block indent|\n{{legend|#510000| > 1 case per 1,000 inhabitants}}\n{{legend|#900000| 1\u201310 cases per 10,000 inhabitants}}\n{{legend|#c80200| 1\u201310 cases per 100,000 inhabitants}}\n{{legend|#ee7070| 1\u201310 cases per 1 million inhabitants}}\n{{legend|#ffC0C0| 1\u201310 cases per 10 million inhabitants}}\n{{legend|#fefee9| 1\u201310 cases per 100 million inhabitants}}\n{{legend|#eee| No confirmed cases}}|left = 3}}\n{{collapsed infobox section begin|Total confirmed cases map}}\n| map2            = COVID-19 Outbreak World Map.svg{{!}}upright=1.5\n| legend2         = {{Center|Map of total confirmed cases as of 21 March 2020}}\n{{Block indent|\n{{legend|#510000| 10,000+ confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#900000| 1,000\u20139,999 confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#c80200| 100\u2013999 confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#ee7070| 10\u201399 confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#ffC0C0| 1\u20139 confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#eee| No confirmed cases}}|left = 3}}\n{{collapsed infobox section end}}\n{{collapsed infobox section begin|Deaths per capita map}}\n| map3            = COVID-19 Outbreak World Map Total Deaths per Capita.svg{{!}}upright=1.5\n| legend3         = {{Center|Map of deaths per capita as of 20 March 2020}}\n{{Block indent|\n{{legend|#980043|100+ deaths per million inhabitants}}\n{{legend|#dd1c77|10\u2013100 deaths per million inhabitants}}\n{{legend|#df65b0|1\u201310 deaths per million inhabitan